{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_buttercup_ver01/data/sn83045012/00340580527/1937120301/0698.xml":{"full_text":"w.\ni-\nHERE'S A LITTLE\nBOOK VOU MIGHT TAKE\nALONG TO THE NEXT\nSESSION AND IT\nWOULDN'T HURT TO\nREAD EACH CHAPTER\nTWICE\nI: Y\nK\n(Copyright, W. Jf. I\nWashington, D. C. (ILNS)\u2014Presi\ndent William Green, of the American\nFederation of Labor, has repudiated\nthe wage and hour bill now reposing\nin the pigeonhole of the rules com\nmittee of the house, and demanded\nthat it be sent back to the labor com\nmittee for complete rewriting. The of\nficial summary pf his objections to\nthe measure follows:\n1. The federation cannot and will\nnot endorse the bill until it has been\nchanged or amended to preserve its\nfundamental objectives, without pos\nsibility of distortion, as the construc\ntive force contemplated by President\nRoosevelt's message of May 24, 1937.\n2. Recent experiences with the Na\ntional Labor Relations Board and the\npresent business recession have com\npelled the federation to qualify its\nposition of last August that the bill\nwas \"fairly satisfactory to labor.\"\nFor Amendments to Shorten Hours\n3. The federation feels as a result\nof the administration of the national\nlabor relations act by the National\nLabor Relations Board that it is no\nlonger safe to permit a government\nboard of that kind to make the many\ndeterminations necessary in the ad\nministration of the fair labor stand\nards bill as now written.\n4. Because the unemployment prob\nlem is rapidly becoming more serious\nas a result of the present business\nrecession, the federation believes the\nbill should be amended to provide for\na shorter work day and a shorter\nwork week.\nPork Sausage\u2014\nLb\nPure Lard-\nLb\nVOL. XXXVII. No. 35 HAMILTON, OHIO\nSome Good Advice\nGreen Declares Federation Opposition to Meas\nure in Present Form, Scores Government\nBoards and Calls for Changes to Shorten\nWork Periods Because of Business Decline,\nCHICAGO MARKET CO.\nF. of L. Demands Wage-Hour Bill\nGo Back to House Labor Committee\nFor Fundamental Amendment\nFederal Boards Sharply Criticized\n5. The federation feels that the\nbasic changes necessary to pveserve\nthe objectives of the bill can receive\nthe required thorough consideration\nonly before the house labor commit\ntee, and therefore recommends that\nthe draft be sent back to that com\nmittee for amendments or for the sub\nstitution of a new bill.\nThe denunciation of government\nboards in general and of the NLRB\nin particular is even stronger in the\ntext of the letter than in the official\nsummary given. In the text of Mr.\nGreen's letter to Mrs. Mary Norton,\nchairman of the house labor commit\ntee, he says that any such plan is\n\"fatally defective.\" He declares that\nthe NLRB has:\n\"Brought turmoil into industrial re\nlations, has usurped the prerogatives\nof the courts essential to the preser\nvation of our democratic form of gov\nernment, and has jeopardized indus\ntrial freedom and initiative.\"\nLewis Gives Qualified Backing\nJohn L. Lewis has given the wage\nand hour bill a qualified approval,\nand strongly urged its passage. He\nsays that it has limitations which\n\"labor cannot permanently accept,\"\nbut:\n\"Recognition of the principle ol\nfederal prohibition of starvation\nwages and oppressive hours of work\nis of such transcendent impoi'tance,\nand the direct benefits of the legisla\ntion will be so great in the area to\nwhich the present bill will apply, that\nPhone 5000\nBaker's 1-Lb.\n..IIV2C Cocoa 15c\n12-Lb. Gold\n..10c Medal 49c\nCalling All Truck, Tractor Auto Owners\nJACK FROST will be your neighbor for the next few months, so\nmake provisions to protect your machines against freezing, and also\nprovide for your own comfort by getting your ANTI-FREEZE,\nHEATERS and all of your parts and supplies at Savage's.\nWe carry a complete line of Heaters, Defrosting Fans, Defrost\ners, Trico Windshields and parts. Delco Batteries, Delco-Remy and\nNortheast Ignition and Starter Parts, Gaskets, Thermostats, Anti\nFreeze.\nSAVAGE AUTO SUPPLY CO.\n636-649 Maple Ave. Phone 116\nHAMILTON, OHIO\u2014A Home Owned Store\nevery effort should be made to brim?\nabout its passage at the earliest pos\nsible moment.\"\nAlex Rose, state secretary of the\nAmerican labor party which elected\nLa Guardia, has wired all New York\nmembers of congress, urging them to\ngive active support to the bill.\nChances Favor Defeat of Bill\nWith this utterly contradictory ad\nvice from labor, what will congress\ndo? No one knows.\nIt is agreed in newspaper circles of\nWashington that the A. F. of L. has\ndecidedly a stronger influence in con\ngress than the CIO. It is agreed, like\nwise, that if the bill is referred back\nto the house labor committee, iu\nbill on that subject will be passed at\nthe special session and the chances\nof one being passed at the regular\nsession following are slim. The tech\nnicalities of procedure in the house\nalso favor those who oppose the bili.\nOn the other hand, a strong effort\nhas been made and is still going on\nby administration supporters to brinti\nthe bill to the floor, and pass it\namended there.\nv,\nHE BUTLER COUNTY PRESS.\nas\nCANADA SEEKS\nUniform Old Age Pension\nPlan\nGreater efficiency in the admini.s\ntration of pensions for the aged in\nCanada was sought at a conference\njust held in Ottawa between officials\nof the Dominion government and the\nprovincial governments.\nUnder the Canadian old age pension\nsystem the Dominion government\npays seventy-five per cent of the cost\nof old age pensions, the provinces\npaying the remaining twenty-five pet\ncent and running expenses under the\nexisting arrangement which provides\nfor administration of old age\nMiners and Operators Warn\nBill to Stabilize Anthracite\nWashington, D. C. (ILNS)\u2014A joint\nconference of United Mine Workers\nofficials, anthracite operators and\ncongressmen from Pennsylvania just\nheld here decided to draw up a new\nbill to stabilize this industry, and pre\nsent it to the regular session of con\ngress. Thomas Kennedy, secretary of\nthe UMW and chairman of the meet\ning, already has named the committee\nto draw up this legislatiin.\nThe UMW is co-operating with the\nanthracite operators and John L. Lewis\nhas suggested that the RFC make\nloans to some of these operators, who\notherwise would be obliged to close\ndown.\nIt is believed probable that state as\nwell as federal legislation will be need\ned and if this becomes clear, the com\nmittee will draft both.\nCITY BOYCOTTS JAP GOODS\nHtill, Yorkshire, Eng. (ILNS)\u2014The\nLaborjte city council has instructed\nall committees and city officials to\ncease buying Japanese goods as a pro\ntest against the bombing of Chinese\ncivilians and open towns and cities.\n5? 4%\nFROM KKEBS!\ni'h-i\npensions\nby the provinces.\nThis plan has been applicable to alt\nprovinces since New Brunswick start\ned participation in the pension plan\nJuly 1, 1936, and Quebec August 1\nof the same year.\nEstimates for the present fiscal\nyear, which ends March 31, 1938, cov\nering 146,524 pensioners, fixed the\nDominion's share of old age pension\ncost at $27,000,000 compared with an\nexpenditure of $21,149,351 for the last\nfiscal year.\nLABOR PEACE CONFER\nENCE AGAIN POSTPONED\nWashington, D. C. (ILNS)\u2014The\npeace conference of committees repre\nsenting the American Federation of\nLabor and the committee for indus\ntrial organization, scheduled to meo\nagain on November 17, was post\nponed by mutual agreement until\nMonday, November 29, at 10 a. m.\nPersons of dis\ncr'mriating taste\nwill immediately\ne o n i z e e s e\ngorgeous Suites\na3 i s i n ctive,\noriginal one-of-a\nkind designs.\nThe qu*lity is apparent in every detail 01 the\ntailorng. The pillows and seats, and the under\nconstruction. Christmas\u2014is the ideal time for\nselecting one for your home. v,\nFRIDAY, DECEMBERS, 1937 ONE DOLLAR PER YEAR\nRevival of\nw\nv\n50\n|i\n'I*#\nUP\nLOUNGl\nI CHAIRS\nONLY\n